{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_haw_ver01/data/sn91068245/00295879014/1908030501/0471.xml":{"full_text":"CAUCASIANo\nj\nVOL. XXVI.\nRALEIGH, NORTH CAROLINA, THURSDAY, MARCH 5. J90S.\nNO.\n8.\nV\"\ni\n\ni ,i\nI\n-I\n4\nV\n1\nat\nThe Indian Court, of Which\nAdams Was Chief Justice,\nUnder Fire in. Congress\nIn the Speech of Congressman Ste\nphens is a Statement That, It la\nCharged that the Indian Citizen\nship Conrt ot Which Adams Was\nChief Justice, Was Bribed Sena\ntor Tillman Offers a Resolution of\nInquiry.\nWashington, D. C, March 3, 190S.\nSpecial to The Caucasian.\nThe Congressional Record contains\na statement that it is charged that\nJudge Adams' Indian Citizenship\nCourt in Indian Territory was bribed.\nThat court was created to determine\nwhich members of the Choctaw and\nChickasaw tribes of Indians were\" en\ntitled to share in a distribution of\nmany millions of dollars of money\nand other valuable property belong\ning to these tribes.\nThe chiefs of these tribes employed\na firm of attorneys to try to have\nstricken from the rolls as many mem\nlcrs of the tribes as possible, so the\nsunount that would go to each person\nsharing in the distribution would be\nincreased. The attorneys were to\nhave their fee increased in propor\ntion to the number kept off the rolls.\nThe Secretary of the Interior pro\ntested againsl the size of the fee\npromised, and also against the in\ncrpase of the fee according to the\nnumber kept off the roll on the\nground that it created a strong in\ncentive to do injustice. The result\nwas that the act creating the conrt\nprovided that the court should fix the\nfees of the attorneys.\nSoon after the court met it is al\nleged that close and intimate relations\nthat seemed to exist between these\nattorneys and Judge Adams began to\nattract attention and the fear began\nto spread that the rights of the In\ndians involved would get but little\nconsideration. The court by its de\ncision struck from the rolls a very\nlarge number of Indians who had al\nwavs been enrolled and recognized as\nmembers of the tribes and who always\nhad shared in their common funds\nand property.\nThis radical decision deprived\nthousands of people, who had always\nbeen recognized both by the Indian\ntribes and also by the government as\nmembers thereof, of over twenty mil\nlions of dollars worth of property.\nThe court followed this action with a\ndecree awarding a fee out of the\nfunds of the Indians to the attorneys\nof seven hundred and fifty thousand\ndollars. The Secretary of the Interior\nat once protested against the action\nof the court and decided to mate an\neffort to try to prevent the payment\nof such a fee for such an object, but\nit was found that under the law creat\ning the court, nothing could be done\nbut execute the law and leave it to\nCongress in the future to right the\nwrong.\nLegislation is now pending in Con\ngress to set aside the action of the\ncourt and to restore to those Indians\nthe property of which they were thus\ndeprived. Congressman Stephens, of\nTexas, making a speech in support\nof this legislation, put into the Rec\nord a statement of facts severely ar\nraigning the action of the court. On\npage 1934 of the Record appears the\nfollowing:\n\"It is alleged that the members of\nthat court were bribed and received\nas a consideration for their decision\na part of the fee paid these attor\nneys.'\nThis sensational statement came a3\nas a great surprise to some, but not\nto those who have kept informed as\nto the situation.\nThis writer has been told by every\nperson who has talked with him\nabout this matter from Indian Ter\nritory or Oklahoma, that it was the\ngeneral sentiment among the people\ndown there that the court action\nwas unjust and contrary to the evi\ndence, and the opinions thus express\ned foreshadow what has at last\nreadied the halls of Congress and has\nattracted national atention and com\n.ment.\nFollowing the speech of Congress\nman Stephens, Senator Tillman, on\nlast Friday offered a resolution of in\nquiry in the Senate reciting what took\nplace in the House as above, and\ncalling upon the Secretary of the In\nterior for information respecting the\nfoundation for such charge.\nIt seems almost certain that Con\ngress will overthrow the action of the\ncourt and restore to the Indians the\nmany millions of dollars worth of\nproperty of which they were deprived\nby the court's decision. It also seems\ncertain that the charge of alleged bri\nbery will be further investigated. The\ndifficulty across the path of an in\nvestigation is to prove the truth of\nthe allegation beyond a reasonable\ndoubt, for as a prominent lawyer\nfrom Oklahoma said to this writer a\nfew days ago, it will be impossible\nof course to prove that the actual\npassing of money from the bands of\nthe attorneys to the hands of any of\nthe judges took place unless one of\nthe parties to such an alleged trans\naction should confess.\nIt is said that there is no- little\ntalk in Greensboro and in other parts\nof the State as to the signs of Judge\nAdams' increased wealth since his\nreturn from Indian Territory. It is\nalso said that when he went away\nfrom Greensboro that he was a poor\nman. He had no known occupation\nwhile in Indian Territory except that\nof chief justice of the court that\npassed on the rights of these Indians\nand fixed the fees of attorneys.\nThe candid observer of human ac\ntion and environment cannot refrain\nfrom looking at the circumstances as\ndescribed at botb ends of the line and\ndrawing logical conclusions there\nfrom. Ohio Solid For Taft.\nColumbus, 0., Special. Secretary\nTaft will go to Chicago with a solid\nBuckeye delegation of forty-six be\nhind him, as a result of the State\nconvention held here Tuesday. The\nState convention was solidly for Taft,\nevery one of the 81i delegate were\nistructed for the Secretary. Little\nlie rest was manifested in the con\neatirii, as the programme was car\nud out without, opposition.\nBeech Hargis Trial Called at Jack\nton. Jackson, Ky., Specials The case\nof the Commonwealth against Beech\nHargis, chaiged with the murder of\n'lis father, former Judge James\nP. Havais, one of the principals in\nhe BreafhiU county feuds, was call\ned Monday before Jrdgc Adams. At-\nC'lney A. Floyd B.yid was engaged\nby the citizens of Jackson to prose-\nute Hargis and will assist \"the coun\nsel for 'he Stle.\nJIany Hurt in Wreck in Texas.\nLaredo, Tex., Special. Four per\nsons were seriously injured and 2\nothers hurt early Tuesday when\nCharles G. Gates' Mexican touring\ntrain was ditched 12 miles north of\nhere. Most of the passengers were\nfrom Toledo, 0., and the middle West,\nThe wreck was caused by the engine's\naxle breaking. Nine eoaches of the\ntrain were ditched.\nOLD SUIIG EOX\nFound Coffee Caused Hands to Trem\nble. The surgeon's duties require clear\nJudgment and a steady hand. A slip\nor an unnecessary incision may do ir\nreparable damage to'tbe patient.\nWhen he found that coffee drink\ning caused hi? bands to tremble, an\nIlls, surgeon conscientiously gave it\nup and this is his story:\n\"For years I was a coffee drinker\nuntil my nervous system was nearly\nbroken down, my hands trembled so 1\ncould hardly write, and insomnia tor\ntured me at night.\n\"Besides, bow could 1 safely per\nform operations with unsteady hands,\nusing knives and instruments of pre\ncision? When 1 saw plainly the bad\neffects of coffee, I decided to stop it,\nand three years ago I prepared some\nPostum, of which I had received a\nsample.\n\"The first cupful surprised me. It\nwas mild, soothing, delicious. At\nthis time 1 gave some Postum to a\nfriend who was in a similar condition\nto mine, from the use of coffee.\n\"A few days after, I met him, and\nhe was full of praise for Postum, de\nclaring he would never return to cof\nfee, but stick to Postum. We then\nordered .a full supply, and within a\nshort time my nervousness and con\nsequent trembling, as well as insom\nnia disappeared, blood circulation be\ncame normal, no dizziness nor heat\nflashes.\n\"My friend became a Postum en\nthusiast, bis whole family using it ex\nclusively. ii\n\"AX would be the fau one\nwho brewed the Postum Ix ty\"\ntaste good when served. f\n\"The best food may be spoijea\nnot properly' mad a\"- Postum. snould\nbe boiled according to directions on\nthe pkg. Then it Is all right, any one\ncan rely on it; It ought to become\nthe national drink,\" \"There's a Rea\nson.\" Name given by Postum Co.,\nBattle Creek, Mictu Read \"The Road\nto WellTUle.- to pkgfc\nBISHOP DUNCAN DIES\nOne of the Ablest Preachers\nof His Church\nWAS BISHOP FOR MANY YEARS\nDied at His Home In Spartanburg\nMonday Morning All the Mem\nbers of His- Family Were at His\nBedside When the End Cam.\nSpartanburg, S. G, SpeciaL Bish\nop W. W. Duncan, of the Methodist\nEpiscopal Church, South, died here\nMonday morning at 0:55 o'clock. The\nfuneral services will be held in Cen\ntral Methodist 'church, this city, oa\nWednesday. The hour for the funer\nal has not been fixed. Bishop Duncan\nbas been hovering between life and\ndeath for severel days and it was only\nby the use of stimulants' that his life\nwas prolonged as long as it was. Hi\ndeath, while a great blow to the mem\nbers of his family and the Methodiat\nchurch, was not uneypeeted. He had\nbeen in bad health for more than a\nyear. Twelve months ago he suffered\nfrom an abscess on the back of his\nneck and his life was despaired of\nat that time. He recovered from the\nattack, but was never restored to\nhealth. About three weeks ago he\nwas taken seriously ill and grew\nsteadily weaker until his death. All\nthe members of his family were at\nthe deathbed.\nBishop Duncan was bdrn at Randolph-Macon,\nVa., December 30th,\n1830, being the third son of Prof.\nDavid Duncan. He received his esrly\neducation at Randolph-Macon, which\nwas completed at Wofford College,\nwhere he graduated in 1S53. After\nbeing converted he studied for the\nministry and upon being admitted\nwas appointed to Eliabeth City, N.\nC, which at that time belonged to\nthe Virginia Conference.\nChaplain in Southern Army.\nDuring the Confederate war he was\nchaplain in the Confederate army.\nFrom the time he entered the minis\ntry he proved a bard and zealous\nworker and filled a number of im\nportant charges. For a number of\nyears he occupied the chair of mental\nand moral, philosophy at Wofford\nand was also financial agent of that\ninstitution. The degree of doctor of\ndivinity was conferred upon him by\nCentral College, Missouri, and Emory\nCollege, Georgia. In the years 1878\nS2 and of 86 he was a member of\nGeneral Conference and in 1881 he\nrepresented his Church at the\nEcumenical Conference held in Lon\ndon, England.\nThe funeral services will be con\nducted in Central Methodist church\nWednesday afternoon at 3 o'clock by\nRev. Dr. J. C. Kilgo, president of\nTrinity College, Durhamf N. C, as\nsisted by well-known Methodist min\nisters. Dr. Kilgo is in New York but\nwill reach Spartanburg in time. The\nfuneral will be one of the largest\never held in the city, as many minis\nters from various places .will be\npresent.\nBishop Duncan was chairman of\nthe board of trustees of Wofford\nCollege and the college in respect to\nhis memory suspended exercises un\ntil Thursday morning. All the stu\ndents will attend the funeral in a\nbody.\nBishop Duncan is survived by his\nwife (who was Miss Medora Rice),\none brother and three children. His\nchildren are Thomas C. Duncan, of\nUnion Mrs. A. G. Rembert and Mrs.\nWarren Dupre of this city.\nCan't Find Hidden Fortune.\nMonmouth, HI., Special. Unsuc\ncessful attempts have been made to\nuncover the $100,000 in gold believed\nto have been buried near the home\nof the late Benjamin Scull, an eccen\ntric citizen of this county. Scull losl\nthe power of speech before his death\nand was unable to tell where his for\ntune was hidden.\nPriest Guarded by Detectives.\nChicago, Special. Plain clothes\ndetectives and uniformed policemei.\nboth guarded a number of the Catho\nlic priests in this city to and froia\ntheir churches on Sunday by request.\nDuring the services officers were sta\ntioned on each side of the altar in the\nBohemian and Italian quarters of\nChicago. Trouble growing out of the\nassassination of the Denver priest\nand the subsequent denunciation of\nanti-clericals were feared. No ar\nrests were made.\nIllness of the British Premier..\nPr r.Ho Prima Minister\n1 Sir Henry--- Campbell Bannerman is\n\"Uying Vejy slowly, froift a relapse\ntfered. ie5ontIy and his physicians\ndo rjfc conceal the uneajdnesswhich\nthey fecoiieerr\nHeart .weakness is an alarming feat\nure of his illness. The serious state\nof his health is reviving-the talk of\nhis retirement\nf- V\",\nI i TTZ -S\nCOST OF CONTROVERSY\nWhat the Eailway Bate Diput Cos\nthe State Interesting rifures\nFrora the Books of the State Audi\ntor. Raleigh Special to The Charlotte\nChronicle\nAn examination of the State\nAuditor's books reveals the fol\nlowing figures of expense in connec\ntion with the cost of the controversy\nbetween the State and liairosd com\npanies in the railway rate litigation.\nTotal -litigation erpense to State\n$13,829.\nPaid to lawyers:\nF. A. Woodard $3 933\nE. J. Justice 3,750\nJ. E. Shepperd M\nAycock Daniels 3,150\nWinston Bryant 1,517\nMerriman Merriaian 835\nS. G. Ryan 2jQ\nOther items:\nStenographer and auditing ser\nvices 3,086\nUnited States Court costs 753\nAttorney General and assistant 36\nPrinting 185\nThe cost of the extra session of the\nLegislature is yet to be added, which\nwill fully double the amount, bring\ning up the total expense to the State\nto $38,000 or more, into which the\n$17,500 the railways offered and the\nGovernor accepted is to be thrown\nand this will bring the actual ex\npenses to the State to less thau\n$23,003.\"\nFriday's Charters.\nRaleigh, Special. Among the new\ncharters issued Friday is one for\nthe Buckstone Lodge Association,\nManchester, Cumberland county, with\na capital of $50,000. The incorpora\ntors ar J. H. Alexander, of Eliza\nbeth, New Jersey; Henry D. Spears,\nNew York; W. Strother Jones, Red\nHank, N. J. James F. Jordan,\nGreensboro.\nThe Bradsha-sv Electric Company,\nCharlotte, amends its charter, chang\ning its name to \"The Tdeal Electric\nCompany.\"\nThe Hamilton Drug Company,- of\nOxford, is also chartered.\nMAIN BUILDING BURNED.\n$4,000 Fire Less Sustained By Indus\ntrial Union Training School at\nSouthrn Pines.\nRaleigh, N. C, Special.\nThe main building of the Industrial\nUnion Training School and Orphan\nage was destroyed by fire early this\nmorning, the total loss amounting to\nabout $4,000. The building, pipe or\ngan, furniture,-etc., were a total loss.\nThis school is for the industrial\ntraining of colored youth and is un\nder the supervision of Rev. J. M\nHenderson, president. The institu\ntion had the endorsement of Grover\nCleveland and other eminent men.\nNews and Observer, Raleigh, N. C.\nThe Building of the Southbound.\nWinston-Salem, Special The\nbuilding of the Southbound Railroad\nfrom Winston-Salem to Wadesboro is\nnow being agitated all along the line.\nThe people look upon it as a \"good\nthing\" for every section through\nwhich it would pass. It is reported\nthat Lane Bros., railroad contractors,\nwho double-tracked for the Southern,\nare now engaged in preparing a bid\nfor construction work on the South\nbound. Looking Into Immigrativ-\nRaleigh, Special. Agents of the\nUnited States Immigration Commis\nsion from Washington, Messrs. Kel\nlett, Ball and Bacon, are in Raleigh\non official business. While in !;orth\nCarolina they will also visit Wilming\nton, Charlotte, Winston, Faj-ettevillc\nand some other points. They say they\nfind out people favor a restricted im\nmigration, limited to desirable classes.\nBond Secured For Men Charged With\nMurder. s\nChester, Special. Messrs. S. E.\nMeFadden and A. L. Gaston attor\nneys for W. G. Dye and Henry Gib\nson, Iwo of the young men charged\nwith killing Reuben Douglas, colored,\na few days ago near Richburg while\nattempting to. arrest one of hia sons,\nappeared before Judge R. C. Watts at\nWinnsboro and secured bond Cz.' their\nclients in the sum of $500 each, the\nmotion not being resisted by the soli\ncitor. The bond was readily furnish\ned, and the young men are again at\nliberty.\nThe Newr kLParasraphs.\nQueen Wilhelminia of Holland and\nher husband escaped injury when a\ntrolley car hit their carriage.\nThe czar told allegation from the\nIJouma property rights nlust be in\nviolate. j\nJapanese are said to be back of a\nreported revolt ih India and Ceylon.\nAn arraignment of anarchists jyas\nmade in the funeral sermon ovei\nFather Leo Hinriehs in Deavar.\nANARCHISTS ACTIVE\nChief of Chicago PoScc Has a\nClose Call\nFINALLY SHOOTS HIS ASSAILANT\nIn Desperate Encounter With Un\nknown Anarchist Chief of Police\nShippy, of Chicago, With Eare\nCourage, Kills His Would Be As\nsassin. Chicago, Special. Chief of Po\nlice George M. Shippy, his son, Har\nry, and his driver, James Foley, were\nwounded by an anarchist who at\ntempted to assassinate the police of\nficial in the hall of the latter 's resi\ndence, 31 Lincoln Court, shortly af\nter 9 o'clock Monday morning. The\ndesperate struggle, in which Mrs.\nShippy and her daughter, Georgiotta,\njoined, was termintcd when the\nchief drew his own revolver and kill\ned his asailant. Attempts to identi\nfy the dead man have thus far result\ned in failure. v\nThe attack is believed to have beer,\nthe result of a conspiracy to harm\nofficials who have been active in 'Sup\npressing manifestations of anarch\nin this community. Other city offi\ncials are said to have been threaten\ned and a police spy who recognized\nthe coipse of the man who invaded\nShippy 's home as that of a person\nwho regularly attended anarchists'\nmeetings, asserted that the -man was\nchosen by h't to do away xith noi\nonly the chief of police but Mayor\nE. R. Busse as well. The ramifica\ntions of the plot are ?aid to extend\nto other cities and to be closely con\nnected with the killing of Rev. Leo\nHeinrichs. a Roman Catholic priest,\nwho was shot clown at the altar of\nhis church in Denver.\nHarry Shippy was shot through\nthe breast twice and was probably\nfatally wounded. His father was\nstabbed in the arm, while Foley re\nceived a bullet in the wrist. Mrs.\nShippy was kicked by the desperado,\nbut her hurts are slight.\nFollowing the attack, squads of po\nlice were sent into the Italian and\nGhetto quarters of the city. Places\nknown as headquarters of secret so\ncieties suspected of anarchistic ten\ndencies were raided and a score or\nmore arrests were made.\n-'As I opened the door,\" said Chief\nShippy later, \"the man raised his hat\nand I allowed him to step into the\nhallway. He handed me an enve\nlope. I glanced at it and then the\nthought struck me that the man was\nup to some wrong. He looked like\nan anarchist. I grabbed his arm3\nand called to my wife who was in\nanother room. When she ran into\nthe hallway I said: 'Mother, see if\nthis man has a revolver,' She felt\nin one of his pockets and said that\nhe had.\n\"I tried to hold him with one\nhand and draw my revolver with the\nother, but he jerked away and fell\nagainst the door. I caught him again\nand while we were struggling my son,\nwho was upstairs, started to my aid.\nHe was only a few steps from the\nbottom of the stairs, when the man\nfreed one hand, drew him revolver\nand fired two shots at Harry. Then\nFoley, who had been summoned by\nmy daughter, stepped into the hall\nand the man shot him. The anarch\nist kicked my wife to one. side and\nby this time I had got my own re\nvolver, and both Foley and I opened\nfire. At my first shot, which struck\nhim in the' head, he fell. But fired\nthree more, one into his head and\ntwo into his body. Two of Foley's\nSJiUlS SUM! oil Uvri vixv oooaou\nClothiers in Session..\nNew York, Special. Clothing \"deal\ners from the Atlantic to the Pacific\nare in attendance at the national con\nvention of the National Association\nof Clothiers, which opened a two\ndays' session in New York. The ses\nsion will be devoted mainly to a dis\ncussion of trade topics.\nSteamer Runs Aground. -New\nYork, Special. The steamer\nSoamo of the New York and Porto\nRico liner inward bound from San\nJuan with a hundred and one passen\ngers aboard, 'went ashore on the Long\nIsland coast between Lone Hill and\nFire Island life-saving stations. She\nwas twenty mile out of her course\nwhen she struck during a thick fog\noverhansiu? the harbor. Life-savers\nare standing by with apparatus in\ncase v of need. She carried a crew of\nfifty.\nKills Wife With Axe.\nWilson, N.' C, SpeciaL Monday\nnidmlng, n$ar here, Will Lewis, a\nwhite faxer, while djrunk, knocked\nbis wife, in the bead -with an axe,\nkilling her... Lewis had been dxiaki\nheavily for a week and on several\noccasions threatened to kjjl hi wue\nand children. Lewis made his es\ncape,: but officers are confident oi\ncapturing him.; Bloodhounds are be\ning: used.\nROADS TO COMPLY\nAgree to Adopt the Nine-Hour\nSystem Without Delay\nCLAIM IT WILL WORK BADLY\nKew Order of Affairs Will Mean the\nEmployment of Thousands of Ad\nditional Operators, the Closing o!\na T arfe Number of Small Stations,\nand General Inconvenience to the\nTrarelin and Shippic Public\nWashington, SpeciaL American\nrailways have made arrangements to\ncomply with the provisions of the\n\"nine-hour law.\" The operation of\nthe law will mean the employment\nby railroad companies of several\nthousand additional operators and\nthe dosing of a large number of\nsmall stations on the 4th of March.\nThe discontinuance of railway ser\nvice at many points, it is realized,\nwill induce at least temporary incon\nvenience to the traveling aud ship\nping public, bit, iu order to reduce\noperating expenses which now seems\nnecessary, the operating officials of\nthe railways believe that this is the\nonly way they posihle can meet the\nsituation with which they are con\nfronted. Astonishing Statements.\nDuring the hearing of applications\nfor an extension of the nine-hour law\nby the winter-State commerce commis\nsion some astonishing statements\nwere made by the operating officials\nof important railways. A good many\nlines, owing to a reduction in their\nrevenues, and to thejr inability to\ncommand the cash necessary to meei\ntheir pay rolls, have been forced,\nduring the past four months, almost\nto the point of asking for receivers.\nIn the opinion of railway officials ex\npressed at the hearing under oath\nand in private conversation this con\ndition does not seem to have been\ndue to the enforcement of legislative\nlaws or to the incapacity of railway\nmanagement. Most of the railroad\nofficials- attribute the difficulty to the\nunfortunate banking situation which\ndeveloped last September. The rail\nways did not feel the stringency iu\nmoney until about the 1st of Novem\nber. In fact, the month of October\nwas one of the best in the history of\nthe business of American railroading.\nOne railway official ventured the\nstatement that in the country to-day\nthere were 300,000 idle freight cars,\nand one line which he instanced was\ndeclared to be hauling empty cars\nbackward and forward because it\nhad not yard room or sidings to ac\ncommodate them.\nNote of confidence.\nNot a single official of a single\nrailway line who appeared before the\ncommission, however, expressed the\nbelief that the present industrial de\npression would be lasting. In the\ntestimony of nearly every witness be\nfore the commision there was a note\nof confidence because all of them\npractically believed that the string\nency in the money market from\nwhich the country has suffered is not\ndue to fundamental causes. They\npoint out that the crops last year\nwere good; that prices were excel\nlent; that industrial enterprises\nthroughout 4he country were flour\nishing. It was merely the inability\nto command ready cash and the\nhoarding of money by -panic-stricken\nindividuals which produced so sud\ndenly the remarkable depression\nfrom which all have suffered. They\npractically uniformly express confi\ndence that the return of prosperity\nwill be almost as sudden as was the\ncoming of adversity and in their ar\nguments as to the enforcement of the\nnine-hour law they pointed out to the\ncommission that such a return of\nprosperity might seriously embarrass\nthem in complying with the law, be\ncause it would render it difficult to\ncommand the services of competent\noperators in sufficient numbers to\nmeet the needs of prosperous condi\ntions. Falls Through Trestle and is Drown\ned. Gaffney, S. C, Special. Coroner\nVinsett was notified that a negro had\nbeen drowned Saturday night in Buf\nfalo creekj'about four miles north of\nGaffney. Accompanied by Dr. J. N.\nNesbitt, the county physician, he re\npaired to the scene and learnedv that\nwhile two drunken negroes were\ncrossing the trestle over Buffalo creek\n(a large and deep stream) one of\nthem fell through.\nProminent Alabama Railroad Man\nDead.\nSelma, Ala., Special. Andjew J\nKiel, 70 years old, die4. at bis resi\ndence in lma, ;Mr. Kiel has been\nassociate with the Southern Railway\nand ks predecessors. 36 years. He\nwas the father of Edward A- Kiel, of\nBuffalo. iT. traffic manager of the\n'TjTTf1? A Knaqpahanna Bailroad.\nflREWBICKS TAMPA\nSeverest Conflagration in the\n&ys History\nEIGHTEEN BLOCKS BURNED CUT\nThr Uanirtd and Eixfct Bafldiaxc\nDestroyed, Eabracicx rift Cixar\nFactcrica, With a Total Loaa Esti\nmated at $000,030,\nTampa, Ha., Spwial The entire\nextreme northeast rrn tum of th\ncity proper ws dftrvVMl by fire,\nwhich raffed until interrupted from\n0 a. m. to 1 p, m. Suuday. The arra\nburned covered 55 arrrs or eighteen\nand one-half city blocks and three\nhundred and eight building were dc\nstroyed, with a total U cctimated at\n$000,000.\nThe burned tctin included futtr\nlarge and one smaller cigar lactone,\nnumerous restauraut. alxn$, board\ning houses and over 200 dwelling oc\ncupied by eignrrnakers. The fac\ntories burned were, M. Staehelberg\nCo., K!s $100,000; M. Wrvt Co.r\nIos .siO,000; (Sonaalcs, Kifher Co.,\nbranch f Stachellx-rg, los $40,000;\nFernandez Hro., lois $J0,(K)0.\nCigar Factories Safer.\nAM factories carried large atoekx\nof tobnecn and eip.nr. The arra\nswept by fire embraced all that por\ntion of the city between 12th and\nMichigan avenues and Sixteenth and\nTwentieth Streets. It originated in\nthe boarding house of Antonio Diai,\n174 Twelfth avenue, and fanned by a\nstrong wind, spread out, fan-fchaped,\ndefxing the efforts of the entire city\nfire department which wa crippled\nby very weak water pressure, owing\nto the smallne8 of the mains iu that\nsection. Occupants of over two\nhundred dwelling houses, thrown in\nto a panic, rushed out, attempting\nto save but little of their belongings\nOne fatality is reported, a Cuban wo\nman in a delicate condition, who\ndrtpjed dead from the shock, bcr\nbody being rescued from the burning\nhouse with difficulty. In the big\nfactories it was possible only to save\nthe most valuable of record, books,\netc., and the valuable stocks of leaf\ntobacco and manufactured cigar,\nready for shipment, were left to the\nmercy of the flames.\nFire Chief Overcome.\nFire Chief Savage wan overcome by\nheat and smoke early in the fire, but\nrecovered later. Citizens volunteered\nassistance to the hard working fire\nmen, but the spread of the flames'\nwas so rapid that little effectual work\ncould be done.\nAmong the buildings, other than\nfactories destroyed, were the hotels\nand cafes of Perez and Castro and\nMaximo Caras, six saloons, 12 restau\nrants and 10 boarding bouses. The\ncar barns of the Tampa F.lectric Com\npany, containing 20 ears, were en\ndangered, and owing to the destruc\ntion of trolly wires cars could not\nbe moved. The big Seirenberj\nbranch factory of the Havanna-Amer-ican\nCigar Company was alo reached\nby the flame but was saved and St.\nJoseph's Catholic Convent and Acad\nemy barely escaped. The fire finally\nburned itself out at the extreme\nnortheastern corner of the city.\nFully half the people rendered\nhomeless were out of work, owing to\nthe dull season in the factories, and\nalso practically out of funds and\ntheir shelter became an immediate\nproblem.\ni\nFromiaent West Virginian Dead.\nMorganton, W. Va., Special Dr.\nEli Marsh Tucker, formerly president\nof West Virginia University, died\nsuddenly Sunday of appoplexy. -He\nbad apparently been in the best of\nhealth and last evening consented to\ntake the nomination for mayor on the\nCitizens party ticket.\nChinese to Surrender Japanese\nSteamer.\nPekin, By Cable. It is announced\nthe Chinese government will surrender-\nthe Japanese steamer Tatsu\n31aru, which was seized on February\n7th by the Chinese customs cruiser\noutside\" of Maeao while unloading a\nbarge consignment of rifk-s and am\nmunition, the rifles numbering several\nthousand. It wa3 originally charged\nthat an attempt was being made to\nbring war supplies into China for\nrevolutionists.\nlim in Brisf.\nTwo bombs were thrown at the\nShah of Persia, one killing .three out\nriders, but the Shah escaped.\n4. bom was thrown at the carriage\nof President Alcorta, of -Arsentuia,\nat Buenos Ayres, but failed to ex\nplode. -y\nThe TVomenV Enfranchisement bill\nfard its first reading in tbe House\nof Commons and was then shelved1 or\nthe rest of the sesaioa.\ni\ni\nI\ni\nt\nt\nI\nI 4","height":"38492","width":"29268"}}
